explanation:
To check MISRA C rule "A function parameter should not be modified" for OS_DeleteAllObjects you need the prototypes/definitions of the functions and macros that appear in its body or could be function-like macros: 

- OS_ForEachObjectOfType: OS_DeleteAllObjects passes &ObjectCount and other arguments to this symbol. Its prototype reveals whether any parameter is a pointer-to-pointer or non-const pointer that could be reassigned by the caller (if it were a macro) or whether the call site could be transformed into code that modifies an argument. Knowing the parameter types also verifies that OS_DeleteAllObjects is not modifying any of its own parameters (it has none) and that it is only passing the address of a local variable (allowed). 

- OS_ForEachObject: same reason as OS_ForEachObjectOfType; OS_DeleteAllObjects calls it with &ObjectCount and constants — need its parameter types/definition to ensure no caller-side parameter modification occurs (e.g., if it were a macro or inline that assigns to an argument expression). 

- OS_TaskDelay: included because it is called from the loop. Its prototype/definition is needed to verify it is a regular function (not a macro) that might expand to code modifying arguments passed at the call site. Also to confirm no parameter of OS_DeleteAllObjects is modified (there are none). 

- OS_CleanUpObject: this function pointer is passed as an argument to the ForEach calls. Its signature is needed to ensure it is not a macro or inline construct that could cause modification of parameters in the caller context, and to understand the semantics of the callback parameter types (pointer vs value). 

- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler: appears in the static call graph from instrumentation/stubs. Include its definition to ensure any test-stub wiring does not expand into code that modifies call-site arguments (macros or inlined stubs). 

- OS_OBJECT_CREATOR_ANY, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMECB, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TASK: the object type/creator symbols passed as arguments could be macros or lvalues; include their definitions to confirm they are simple constants/enums (safe) and not something that could be altered by the call site or be assigned to.

Note: OS_DeleteAllObjects itself has no formal parameters, so it cannot violate the rule by modifying its own parameters. The above symbols are needed to rule out indirect violations caused by macro expansions or unusual definitions of the called symbols that would perform assignments to argument expressions at the call site.
